Abstract â€” English

Recent advances in computational modeling and artificial intelligence have opened new frontiers in human-level physiological simulation and intelligent medical decision support. However, existing systems remain fragmented, disease-centric, and limited to narrow clinical contexts. This work proposes a unified, human-centric Medical AI-FEM Core: a fully integrated architecture that couples Finite Element Modeling (FEM) of biological tissues and organs with an adaptive, transparent, parameter-controlled AI Controller capable of learning, optimization, and predictive guidance across all major physiological systems.

The proposed framework establishes a mathematically-grounded, clinically-interpretable, and modular architecture spanning cardiovascular, respiratory, hepatic, renal, neural, endocrine, immune, musculoskeletal, and integumentary systems, with the ability to extend toward multi-organ and whole-body simulation. The system is designed to support clinical research, personalized treatment planning, digital twin development, and prospective predictive modeling while maintaining medical transparency, safety alignment, and reproducibility.

Key contributions include:
(1) a unified FEM-based physiological modeling structure,
(2) an explainable AI Controller with tunable parameters and safety constraints,
(3) validated biomedical reference modeling steps aligned with medical standards, and
(4) a multi-layer documentation and verification pipeline supporting medical-grade integrity.

This work demonstrates the feasibility of moving from isolated AI tools toward a coherent, medically-grounded intelligent simulation ecosystem, forming the basis for future organic-style adaptive clinical intelligence systems.


