Introduction â€” English

The human body represents one of the most complex dynamical systems known, governed by nonlinear, multi-scale interactions among tissues, organs, and regulatory systems. While artificial intelligence has achieved remarkable progress in pattern recognition, its integration with physically-grounded physiological modeling remains limited. Current medical AI systems are typically disease-oriented, operating as risk calculators, diagnostic classifiers, or isolated decision aids without an integrated physiological core.

Finite Element Modeling (FEM) has long been established as a powerful method for simulating biomechanical behavior and tissue-level interactions. However, FEM systems alone lack adaptive intelligence and individualized learning capacity. This work bridges that gap by proposing a unified architecture that fuses FEM physics-based modeling with adaptive AI-driven clinical intelligence in a medically interpretable framework.

The Medical AI-FEM Core is designed not merely as a tool, but as a foundational infrastructure for intelligent medicine, supporting research, simulation, validation, clinical planning, and future digital twin ecosystems.


