1. English Version

5. Validation Strategy

To ensure scientific rigor, the Medical AI-FEM Core follows a multi-stage validation protocol:

5.1 Numerical Verification

We verify the finite-element solvers using:

analytical benchmark problems

mesh-refinement convergence

energy balance consistency

stability analysis


The solution error norm is evaluated as:

E = \| U_{ref} - U_h \|

Convergence is accepted when:

E \rightarrow 0 \quad \text{as} \quad h \rightarrow 0

where  is the element size.


---

5.2 Physiological Plausibility

Model outputs are compared against:

published physiological ranges

gold-standard measurements

cadaver and imaging studies

prior computational models


Example metrics:

Domain	Variable	Expected Range

Hemodynamics	Wall shear stress	1â€“7 Pa
Lung mechanics	Tidal volume	~500 mL
Brain	Neural conduction delay	1â€“20 ms


Agreement â‰¥ 95% confidence interval is targeted.


---

5.3 Clinical Validation

Prospective validation includes:

anonymized patient datasets

IRB-approved observational trials

outcome-based comparison

clinician-reviewed interpretation audits


Primary endpoints:

âœ” predictive accuracy
âœ” interpretability score
âœ” clinician acceptance
âœ” safety non-inferiority


---

5.4 AI-Controller Safety Validation

The controller is stress-tested under:

extreme input perturbations

missing data

parameter drift

noise injection


Risk is quantified as:

R = P(\text{unsafe}) \cdot S(\text{impact})

and maintained below a clinically acceptable threshold.


---

6. Clinical Relevance

The platform supports:

diagnosis assistance

personalized therapy planning

pre-surgical simulation

ICU scenario modeling

drug response simulation

biomedical research

clinical education and training


Each organ module can function independently
or as part of a whole-body system.


